Reason through the specific problem of ARIA misuse and its implications for automated accessibility testing. ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) was designed to supplement the native HTML accessibility model for complex interactive widgets that HTML alone cannot express. But ARIA is frequently misused in ways that actively harm accessibility rather than improving it.

The first rule of ARIA is "don't use ARIA" — use semantic HTML instead wherever possible. Yet automated accessibility testing tools like axe-core will pass a div with role="button" and an appropriate aria-label, even though the same content as a native button element would be more accessible (native buttons are focusable by default, activate on Enter and Space, are announced consistently across screen readers, and don't require JavaScript to remain functional without CSS). The automated tool sees valid ARIA and passes it; a human expert sees a div-button and flags it.

What is the theoretical limit of an automated ARIA validator? Reason through each category of ARIA misuse and classify whether it is automatable: redundant ARIA on semantic elements (role="heading" on an h1, role="link" on an a), broken ARIA relationships (aria-labelledby pointing to a non-existent ID, aria-describedby on a element with no accessible name, aria-owns creating impossible ownership structures), ARIA that overrides valid native semantics (removing a button's implicit role with role="presentation"), and ARIA live regions that are either over-used (announcing every DOM change causing noise) or under-used (dynamic content updates that are never announced).

Consider the interaction between ARIA validity checking and screen reader behavior: the ARIA spec defines what is valid, but screen reader implementations sometimes deviate from the spec. An ARIA pattern that passes specification validation may still produce poor screen reader output in NVDA+Firefox, VoiceOver+Safari, or JAWS+Chrome. How should an automated ARIA validator communicate this uncertainty?

What is the correct role of automated ARIA analysis in a broader accessibility assurance program, given these fundamental limits?
